<article>

  <p>
    A teaching can harm the person who holds it. That is not a paradox reserved
    for bad doctrines. It is what happens when any doctrine — including a true
    one — is taken by the wrong end: memorised for status, recruited to defend a
    preference, worn as a new name for the old self. The grip does the damage.
    The text does not need to be false to bite.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Alagaddūpama
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sutta" data-en="discourse">Sutta</span>
    (MN 22) is about that grip. It opens with a monk who has rearranged the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dhamma" data-en="teaching">Dhamma</span>
    until it excuses what he wants. It answers with two similes — the snake and
    the raft — and then with an inventory of how identity view is built from the
    five aggregates. The through-line is not a catalogue of metaphors. It is a
    single question: is the teaching being used to cross, or being clutched as
    another object of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="upadāna" data-en="clinging; holding">upadāna</span>?
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Grasped by the Wrong End</h2>

  <p>
    Ariṭṭha has been circulating a convenient reading: the things the Buddha
    calls obstructions are not really obstructions for someone who engages in
    them. The other monks cannot shift him. When the report reaches the Buddha,
    the tone in the Majjhima
    <span class="pali" data-pali="nikāya" data-en="collection">Nikāya</span>
    sharpens. This is not a polite disagreement about emphasis. It is
    misrepresentation born of wrong grasp — the teaching bent until it blesses
    desire.
  </p>

  <p>
    Most of us recognise the pattern without needing a monastery. A rule becomes
    optional the moment it costs something. A restraint is rebranded as
    "attachment to rules." A craving finds a quote. The mind is not seeking
    clarity; it is seeking cover. Of course the cover can sound sophisticated.
    That is part of why it works.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Buddha's first image is the poisonous snake. Catch it by the body or the
    tail and it bites. Catch it with a proper tool, at the right end, and it can
    be held safely. The Dhamma is like that. Grasped for debate, for identity, for
    permission — it wounds. Grasped as training for the ending of craving — it
    does what it is for. The harm is not in the teaching. It is in the end by
    which one takes hold.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Crossing, Not Carrying</h2>

  <p>
    Imagine needing to cross a flood. You bind sticks, grass, and leaves into a
    raft and paddle to the far shore. Having arrived, what should be done with
    the raft?
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "Monks, what do you think? If that person, having crossed to the far shore,
    were to hoist the raft on his head or load it on his shoulder and then walk
    away with it — would that person be doing what should be done with the raft?
    […] The Dhamma is to be used like a raft: for the purpose of crossing over,
    not for the purpose of holding onto."
    <cite>— MN 22 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    The passage is sometimes recruited as Buddhist relativism: teachings are mere
    tools, and tools can be discarded whenever preference says so. That reading
    flatters a modern appetite for freedom from commitment. It is also too easy.
  </p>

  <p>
    What the simile actually mocks is carrying the raft on the head after the
    crossing — treating the vehicle as luggage once the river is behind you. The
    raft is not dismissed. It is used where use is needed, then not hauled where
    haulage is absurd. The Dhamma that gets one to the far shore is the same
    Dhamma one stops clutching as a possession on the far shore. The point is the
    difference between using a path and clinging to a path.
  </p>

  <p>
    That distinction matters because clinging does not only attach to pleasure.
    It attaches to views, to practices, to the story of being someone who
    understands. Even the insight that things are non-self can be collected like a
    badge — another object for a self to own. The raft teaching is not an excuse
    to skip the crossing. It is a warning against making the crossing into a new
    form of holding.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Twenty Ways to Build a Self</h2>

  <p>
    The sutta then turns to
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sakkāyadiṭṭhi" data-en="identity view; view of personal existence">sakkāyadiṭṭhi</span>
    — identity view: taking the body-mind complex as a self. The Buddha does not
    leave this as a vague mood. He maps twenty forms of it, generated by applying
    four patterns to each of the five
    <span class="pali" data-pali="khandha" data-en="aggregate">khandhas</span>
    — form, feeling, perception, formations, and consciousness.
  </p>

  <p>
    For each aggregate the patterns are the same: taking it <em>as</em> self
    ("form is my self"); taking the self as <em>possessing</em> it ("my self has
    form"); taking it as <em>in</em> the self ("form is in my self"); taking the
    self as <em>in</em> it ("my self is in form"). Four patterns, five aggregates:
    twenty views. The interest is not the arithmetic. It is the implication.
    The ways a self can be constructed from the aggregates are finite and
    nameable. There is no leftover proprietor hiding in the gaps between the
    list.
  </p>

  <p>
    The untaught ordinary person relates to the aggregates in one or more of
    these twenty ways. Agitation follows — not as a separate pathology, but as
    the natural weather of a mind that has already decided a fixed self must be
    located across time: Was I in the past? Will I be in the future? What am I
    now? The questions presuppose what they pretend to investigate. They keep
    the search for an owner busy, and the busyness feels like seriousness.
  </p>

  <p>
    The instructed disciple who has heard the teaching and seen the aggregates
    as they are does not hold these views — and therefore does not have to feed
    those anxieties. Not because the questions have been suppressed by effort,
    but because examination has not found what the views were pointing toward.
    The
    <a href="/suttas/anattalakkhana/">Anattalakkhaṇa Sutta</a>
    tests the same ground factor by factor;
    <a href="/concepts/anatta-in-practice/">anattā in practice</a>
    asks what changes when ownership softens mid-reaction. This discourse adds
    the inventory of the clinging itself.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What Gets Set Down</h2>

  <p>
    Ariṭṭha's error, the snake, the raft, and the twenty views are not separate
    essays stapled together. They are one movement. Wrong grasp of the Dhamma is
    clinging dressed as insight. Identity view is clinging dressed as ontology.
    The alternative is not contempt for teaching or for practice. It is use
    without possession — crossing without turning the vehicle into a throne.
  </p>

  <p>
    So the practical question is sharper than "Do I agree with Buddhism?" It is
    whether the teaching has been understood or merely acquired. Using the Dhamma
    to rationalise sensual indulgence is acquisition with a costume. Clinging to
    "I am a practitioner" as a fresh identity is the same costume in quieter
    fabric. Even right
    <span class="pali" data-pali="diṭṭhi" data-en="view">diṭṭhi</span>
    is, in the end, to be lived and released — not hoarded as proof that one has
    arrived. Notes, not a finished self-portrait.
  </p>

  <p>
    The path to the far shore requires the raft. Standing on the near bank
    admiring the craftsmanship does not get anyone across. What matters is
    whether attention is still busy polishing a view — or whether the view is
    doing the quieter work of letting go.
  </p>

</article>
